Stage 1
	It's extremely difficult to cover every possible program and execution
details. Thus, some compromises have to be made: Mirage first splits the input
program into Lax subprograms, which reduces the search space drastically while
still preserving many optimization opportunities.
---------
Stage 2
	Now Mirage can exhausively search for programs with the Lax compromise, but
the search space is still much larger than those of previous works. Thus,
intensive pruning is needed, by "abstract expressions."
	Still, as an exception, for the thread-level, mirage is still using a
rule-based approach.
	Yet another compromise, not on search space, but on equivalence, is made:
Mirage only performs random tests over finite fields (I guess it means finite
input space). But Mirage does provide a theoretical bound of strong
correctness, thanks to the Lax compromise.
